{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ceea6c90-26b4-4166-b997-7b4191463ebd","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse reports with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — These are disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file will appear at the configured path.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — You can attach or load a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /path/to/core\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report (JSON format) is usually the quickest path — it includes the stack trace, faulting thread, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f50b5e36-39da-403b-845f-2b345e4b9d8b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":347,"requestId":"A0C3:2FD5E:5B300:6C6A8:6A0136B6"},"id":"c042af4b-dea1-447d-9f38-70a495a5a6a7","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:54:07.655Z","parentId":"6681904f-5fe8-49ac-80cb-951a24a6d9ad"}
